age, has broad implications for the linguistic dating of Biblical texts. The presentations are rounded out by useful summary histories of linguistic diachrony in Aramaic, Ugaritic, and Akkadian, the three languages related to and considered most crucial for Biblical research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAndersen, Francis I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-Asher Siegal, Elitzur A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloch, Yigal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Chaim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDresher, B. Elan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrensvärd, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassberg, Steven E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForbes, A. Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGivón, T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmstedt, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurvitz, Avi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoosten, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKouwenberg, N. J. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLam, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller-Naudé, Cynthia L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller-Naudé, Cynthia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNaudé, Jacobus A., econtributor.